<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26090k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26090k">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26090k"> 90(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sparver</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It will be noticed that Elizabeth took with her not only a lump sum of money, but also clothes and a bed, the cost of which more than doubled the dowry. Canon law specifically allowed the provision of a habit by friends, when the poverty of a house rendered this necessary; and it is clear from other sources that it was not unusual for a novice to be provided also with furniture. The inventory of the goods belonging to the priory of Minster in Sheppey, at the Dissolution, contains, under the heading of &ldquo;the greate Chamber in the Dorter,&rdquo; a note of stuff in the same chamber belonging to Dame Agnes Davye, <i>which she browghte with her</i>; a square <mark>sparver</mark> of payntyd clothe and iiij peces hangyng of the same, iij payre of shets, a cownterpoynt of corse verder and i square cofer of ashe, a cabord of waynscott carved, ij awndyrons, a payre of tonges and a fyer panne. <small> Eileen Edna Power, <a name="MLEN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MLEN"><cite title="source">Medieval English Nunneries</cite></a> (1922) 20</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
